h of their time thinking in verse and about verse, these original essays herald the return of the early modern lyric as crucial to understanding the present moment of poetry in the United States. This work provides fascinating insights into what today's poets find of special interest in their forebears. In addition, these discussions shed light on the contributors' own poetry and offer compelling clues to how the poetry of the past continues to inform that of the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnglish literature. 0aEnglish poetryyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aacademic.  aanne bradstreet.  aben jonson.  acontemporary poetry.  acontemporary poets.  acreative writers.  acreative writing.  aearly modern lyric.  aearly modern poetry.  aessay anthology.  aessay collection.  ajohn donne.  aliterary history.  aliterary.  alyric poems.  alyric poetry.  amargaret cavendish.  amfa.  amilton.  aphilip sidney.  apoetic form.  apoetics.  apoetry studies.  ascholarly.  asestina.  asonnet.1 aBedient, Calvin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoland, Eavan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFulton, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregerson, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunn, Thom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHass, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHecht, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLogan, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMchugh, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc